title: Slidr
text:
Slidr
For many non-design professionals, creating slides is a recurring, high-friction task. While slides are meant to efficiently communicate ideas, the process of structuring content, aligning with design standards, and preparing delivery scripts is time-consuming and mentally taxing. As expectations around productivity increase, many teams turn to AI to reduce this overhead. However, slide creation remains a challenging problem for automation due to its reliance on context, audience awareness, and design judgment. Significant thought and effort is required in each phase of the process: Structuring content, Design and Deliverance.

title: Slidr
text:
Slidr > Competitive Space
Nowadays many automated tools have been created to fill this gap (such as: SlideGO and SlidesGPT). However, most are arguably sub-par, and usually only target a singular phase of the process. Creating a general  slide generation tool is incredibly challenging. This is due to the vast differences in presentations due to style (design, delivery) and context (audience, specific company requirements, etc). Hence, most of the time, these tool will eventually generate simplistic slides (like bullet points on a colour background) which are not usable or require significant edits.

title: Slidr
text:
Slidr > Powerpoint Generator 
To address this issue, we decided to create a personalised slide generation tool. This tool should be able to adapt to the specific requirements of each user/company, account for different audiences, and address each phase of the slide creation process. It would be ideal (an absolute miracle) if we were able to create an end-to-end tool that delivered on all above requirements and produced perfect slides that require little to no edits. More realistically, we intend to create a tool that helps overcomes the initial inertia to slide creation, to create something personalised that employees can build upon, allowing them to focus on more important details in the presentation.

title: Slidr
text:
Slidr > Key Insight: Slide Fitting Over Slide Generation
After we started building the tool, we quickly realised it was extremely challenging to generate ‘good’ slides from text, even with a detailed prompt with appropriate context. Most AI tools function well when given a specific set of instructions and parameters to complete a sequential almost algorithmic task but fail spectacularly when it comes to open ended tasks that require creativity or more nuance, such as exploration or in this case design. 

To remedy, this we chose a different approach: Slide Fitting. In this approach, the user will upload a set of general pre-formatted slide templates (or choose from defaults we provide) and the tool will then decide which slide template is most appropriate for each part of the content and fit the content to the slide. Before you start frowning, hear me out. Disregarding the obvious disadvantage of having to manually create the initial deck of side templates, there are many benefits to this approach. For example, companies would be able to input specific templates that they require in all presentations, like a security classification on each slide, or a recommended standard presentation flow. This uniformity ensures coherence and standardisation across the board, allowing users to focus more on the message to be delivered. We acknowledge that this will not hold for ALL users, (i can already hear my friends from Figma __) but we believe that in places where the focus of presentations is to solely convey a message (rather than dazzle), this tool would be a great help.

title: Slidr
text:
Slidr > Key Insight: Slide Fitting Over Slide Generation
(I also believe some of us {the less artistically inclined},  and our audience, may benefit from such an approach. Designers can design, and we can just reuse professionally designed slide template and focus on our delivered message.)

title: Slidr
text:
Slidr > Preserving User Control Through a Layered Design
To preserve user control while still leveraging automation, we designed Slidr as a three-layer system. This is to ensure that users have control at each stage to make necessary edits so that the final generated slides is as optimal as possible. This is done in three layers: 1. Content Generation 2. Slide Analysis 3. Slide & Script Generation. The quality of output of these tools is largely dependent on input, hence, we first guide our users to build a good prompt, by allowing them to set the required tone, target audience and most importantly provide any relevant documents pertaining to the presentation. With this context, we generate the content of the presentation, focused on structure and flow. Once done, we present the generated structure back to the user for editing and clarification. Only after the user is satisfied, we continue to section the content into different slides.  Secondly, we analyse the slide template provided, and identify what kind of content each slide might best represent. For example a slide with just a big header and a caption might be used as a title/ opening slide.  Thirdly, for each section, we then split the content into “to say” and “to show” categories. Thereafter, we match the slide that best represent the “to show”content of the section, and fit each part of the content to the slide. Finally, we take all the “to say” content and generate a script befitting of the audience, length of presentation and tone provided.

title: Slidr
text:
Slidr > Success Definitions
Users were able to generate a structured, template-aligned deck significantly faster than starting from a blank slide.

title: Slidr
text:
Slidr > Success Definitions
Compared to existing AI slide tools, generated slides required fewer layout and formatting changes, as they were already aligned with company-approved templates.

title: Slidr
text:
Slidr > Success Definitions
Users reported feeling more confident editing and extending the generated slides, as the structure and design choices were transparent and predictable.

title: Slidr
text:
Slidr > Success Definitions
While this was a hackathon project, we defined success around three primary outcomes: Time to First Draft Edit Reduction Perceived Control

title: Slidr
text:
Slidr > Conclusion 
We strongly believe that this novel approach to slide generation makes the most logical sense and would be extremely beneficial to many. With more time, I would focus on increasing user agency in the slide matching process. This can be done by showing users a preview of the generated slides and allowing them to manually swap slide templates for each section. This would allow even more user control so that the final slides are most optimal.

title: My Favorite Hobbies
text:
My Favorite Hobbies
In a world that rarely slows down, I’m drawn to pursuits that offer both challenge and meaning. Sport has taught me perseverance and teamwork, music has given me a creative voice, and giving back has shown me the importance of using my skills in service of others. These experiences collectively shape how I grow, create, and contribute.

title: My Favorite Hobbies
text:
My Favorite Hobbies > Basketball 
I was about eight years old when I first laid my eyes on a basketball, and from that moment on, I was completely hooked. What began as casual play quickly grew into an obsession—I was glued to the game, thinking and dreaming about basketball at every opportunity. I played competitively until I was 18, pouring countless hours into training, matches, and improving my craft. Growing up, I was deeply inspired by Allen Iverson. His crossover wasn’t just a move—it was a statement. As a smaller player overcoming the odds, he embodied grit, fearlessness, and the belief that heart could outweigh physical disadvantage. That mindset resonated strongly with me and shaped how I approached both the game and challenges beyond it. However, my competitive journey was not without setbacks. Multiple injuries, including a dislocated knee, eventually forced me to step away from high-level play. While my time on the court diminished, my love for the sport never did. Basketball remains a core part of who I am—an enduring passion that taught me resilience, humility, and the value of relentless effort.

title: My Favorite Hobbies
text:
My Favorite Hobbies > Taekwondo
In my freshman year of college, I found myself at a crossroads. I missed the rigour, camaraderie, and thrill of competitive team sports, yet I had become increasingly aware of my body’s limitations after years of basketball-related injuries. My desire to push myself physically remained strong, but I needed a discipline that demanded control as much as intensity. That was when I discovered Taekwondo, and more specifically, Poomsae. Poomsae is the art of executing structured patterns that simulate combat scenarios, emphasising precision, balance, timing, and intent. Each sequence consists of carefully choreographed movements—blocks, strikes, stances, and kicks—performed with exacting control and expressive power. What started as exploration quickly turned into commitment. I trained regularly, up to four times a week, and soon found myself immersed in a tight-knit team of dedicated athletes and coaches. The environment pushed me to refine not only my physical technique but also my mental focus and discipline. Before long, I was representing my university at varsity-level competitions. In my first competition, I won a gold medal in the pairs category and a silver in the team category. The following event exceeded all expectations—I secured three gold medals across the singles, pairs, and team categories, and was honoured as the Best Male Poomsae Player of the entire competition. More than the accolades, however, Taekwondo gave me lifelong friendships and a renewed appreciation for mastery through patience and consistency.

title: My Favorite Hobbies
text:
My Favorite Hobbies > Music
Music has always been a constant presence in my life. I grew up listening to my dad play ABBA in the car, along with his deep appreciation for classic rock and timeless melodies. Those early drives became an informal introduction to music that valued strong songwriting, rhythm, and emotion. As a result, my musical upbringing was rooted in older artists and bands such as The Beatles, Queen, ABBA, and Elvis Presley. Long before discovering modern genres, I learned to appreciate musicality, harmony, and groove through these classics, forming a foundation that would later guide my own journey as a musician. In college, I picked up the bass guitar, initially out of curiosity, but quickly developed a deep appreciation for the instrument. The bass taught me how to listen—how rhythm and groove quietly hold everything together. Over time, I grew to love its understated yet essential role in shaping the feel of a song. Through playing the bass, I discovered a genre that resonated with me deeply: funk. Its emphasis on tight rhythms, pocket, and feel aligned perfectly with what I enjoyed most about music. My favourite band, Vulfpeck, and bassist Joe Dart in particular, became major inspirations. I had the opportunity to perform several times for my course and orientation events, with my largest performance taking place during my college open day—an experience that cemented my love for performing live.

title: My Favorite Hobbies
text:
My Favorite Hobbies > Music
After another career-ending ankle injury, I found myself sidelined in the winter of 2025, stuck in a boot and relying on crutches. Unable to train or perform physically, I turned to music in a different way. My roommate owned a DJ controller, and I began experimenting with it out of boredom and curiosity. What started as casual fiddling soon became an engaging creative outlet. DJing allowed me to explore music through energy, transitions, and crowd dynamics, offering a new perspective on how sound can shape atmosphere and emotion. It became a way to stay connected to music during a period of forced stillness.

title: My Favorite Hobbies
text:
My Favorite Hobbies > Giving Back 
Meaningful work drives me. Knowing that my efforts can directly improve the lives of people who need it most is deeply motivating. Beyond technical challenge, I am drawn to projects that create tangible, human impact. In my freshman year of college, I joined REACH (Renaissance Engineers Are Caring Humans). True to its name, the club focuses on building engineering solutions for underserved communities and individuals with specific needs. Over the years, I contributed to multiple projects and eventually served as the club’s President. During my tenure, we launched seven projects in teams of four to six, spanning domains from MedTech to assistive technologies, in collaboration with organisations such as MDAS and AWWA. During my exchange at UC Berkeley, I joined Blueprint, a technology club dedicated to supporting non-profits. As a full stack developer, I worked with a team to build a web application that digitalised emergency preparedness table-top exercises. The project combined my technical skills with my passion for public good, reinforcing my belief that technology is most powerful when it is used in service of others.

title: My Favorite Hobbies
text:
My Favorite Hobbies > Conclusion
Across sports, music, and service, a common thread runs through how I spend my time: a desire to grow, to connect, and to contribute meaningfully. Whether it was pushing my limits on the court, refining precision through Taekwondo, finding rhythm through music, or building technology for social good, each pursuit has shaped how I approach challenges and opportunities. These experiences have taught me resilience in the face of setbacks, humility in learning new disciplines, and fulfilment in working with and for others. Together, they form not just my hobbies, but the values I carry forward such as, curiosity, discipline, and a commitment to making a positive impact wherever I can.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Evolution of EyeTracker
Glaucoma is a chronic, progressive optic neuropathy and is the leading cause of irreversible blindness worldwide. Key to the management of glaucoma is the accurate assessment of visual field (VF) function to detect VF loss, which impacts important clinical decisions with respect to medication titration, laser procedures and even surgery. VF function is commonly assessed using automated perimetry, which relies on controlled light stimuli and repeated patient responses over a sustained testing period.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Evolution of EyeTracker > The Problem Breakdown
However, these tests are not just clinical tools; they are capacity-constrained diagnostic workflows where unreliable results translate directly into wasted appointment slots, delayed care, and downstream clinical risk. After speaking to ophthalmologists to identify the gaps in current practices, we broke the problem down into two parts: Instruction and Execution. Instruction:  The patients that ophthalmologists have the most difficulty with are usually elderly. With this group of people, struggles usually originate from a communicative breakdown. Due to the relative complexity of the test, significant time is spent on clarification, which leads to a stress on manpower. This problem is also exacerbated by potential language barriers and/or hearing impairments. Execution: Given the enclosed nature of the test and that results are not known until the end of the 10 minute long procedure, doctors or nurses would not be able to consistently track and correct any mistakes in execution. Hence, any misunderstandings, unconscious habits or errors will go unidentified and only be reflected in via a failed test.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Evolution of EyeTracker > Proposed Solution 
To address both instruction and execution failures, without increasing clinical burden, we converged on a two-part solution: A simplified instructional video that relies on visual cues rather than spoken language to relay information → This aims to reduces technician explanation variance and offload some communication overhead A pre-assessment simulation booth with immediate haptic feedback and performance statistics  → This allows patients to familiarise with test procedures and environment and allows nurses to identify any potential misunderstandings or errors before the test. This solution should provide standardised, user-friendly instruction for patients, accompanied by hands-on practical practice with immediate sensory or tactile feedback. In totality, this aims to reduce the VF testing learning curve for patients and enhance patient education - thereby improving reliability and consistency of test outcomes.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Evolution of EyeTracker > The Early Prototype
A big problem we we faced was placing the camera at an appropriate location that ensured ample view of the eye while also avoiding the light thrown by the visualiser.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Evolution of EyeTracker > The Early Prototype
The light from the projector reflects back into the pupil causing significant reflection on the pupil itself. This significantly affects the accuracy in pupil detection.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Evolution of EyeTracker > The Early Prototype
Due to the nature of VF testing to obtain accurate results and account for different eyes of movement, the sample rate had to minimally be faster that 60fps. (to account for saccadic eye movement.)

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Evolution of EyeTracker > The Early Prototype
Our initial prototype consisted of several components. In our design, we aimed to adapt current technologies to reduce adoption friction and improve speed of prototyping.  Major components include: Visualiser to screen dots on a white back ground Camera with pupil tracking capabilities Basic electronics such as an Arduino with some buttons to record presses and a buzzer to provide haptic feedback on erroneous presses. Some dark box to ensure ample illumination from the visualiser Simple command-line interface, run script and await results Early prototypes revealed that many technically viable solutions were not user-friendly and intuitive. This forced us to re-anchor design decisions around existing clinical models rather than engineering convenience.  Some challenges we faced: Camera placement Illumination Sample rate and pupil tracker accuracy

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Evolution of EyeTracker > The HI-FI
Over several iterative consultation with our partner ophthalmologists, we realised several flaws associated with the prototype and found that it was not as intuitive to users as we hoped. In response, we intentionally aligned the physical design to existing VF testing hardware to reduce patient confusion and minimise changes to established clinical workflows. List of updated major components: ‘Laser Turret’ to shine spots at particular coordinates  Staged PyQt6 GUI, more intuitive UX, build initialise, start stop into GUI, do not need to touch the terminal Calibration stage to adjust for differences for each patient to ensure test optimality. Adapted pupil tracker with vectorised calculations to improve sampling and frame rate  3D Printed Open Box Design with smoothed edges and a structure to support the existing chin rest used in VF tests.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Evolution of EyeTracker > Learning Points
Aside from the technical growth and exposure to computer vision techniques such as image filtering, thresholding, and feature extraction, this project changed my perspective on building for real-world use. It highlighted the need for developers and builders to take time to abstract themselves from technical details and view the bigger picture on user requirements and standards.  Summary of learning points: User acceptance and workflow fit mattered more than algorithmic sophistication Incremental reliability gains were more valuable than ambitious feature expansion Technical exposure to computer vision methods (i.e. Image filtering, thresholding, feature extraction)  Technical exposure to hardware software interfacing (i.e. Real-time serial communication between Arduino and python script)

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Evolution of EyeTracker > What Now?
Currently, our user testing has been limited to our partner ophthalmologists and nurses. The next critical step would be to begin iterative A/B testing with actual users and validating if this solution translate into fewer failed VF tests.  Once the prototype has been validated, we can move on developing a custom PCB for the hardware and possibly integrate a lightweight GPU for fast processing of images. This would allow more calculations and more accurate detection of different pupils even under poor lighting conditions.

During my time at the Land Transport Authority (LTA), I worked on an internal initiative aimed at improving AI literacy across the organisation. As a traditionally engineering-driven transport agency with long-standing legacy systems, LTA was exploring how artificial intelligence could be responsibly adopted to enhance productivity and decision-making. Rather than immediately deploying AI systems, the focus of this initiative was foundational: to raise awareness, build shared understanding, and encourage informed and appropriate use of AI tools among officers from diverse technical backgrounds.

title: DSO Internshi
text:
DSO Internshi
Due to the sensitive nature of defense-related work, this post will focus on high-level technical themes and engineering decisions rather than application-specific context. During my internship at DSO, I worked with third-party hardware and systems providers to evaluate whether GPU-accelerated solutions could meaningfully improve the performance of existing data-processing pipelines. The goal was not to build a production system, but to experimentally assess feasibility, performance gains, and integration challenges.

title: DSO Internshi
text:
DSO Internshi > Role and Reponsibilities 
I worked as a Software Engineering Intern, focusing on algorithm research, performance optimization, and experimental GPU acceleration.  Responsibilities: Researching density-based clustering algorithms (DBSCAN, HDBSCAN, Mean Shift) Evaluating their suitability for parallel execution Designing and implementing GPU-parallel versions of selected algorithms Benchmarking GPU implementations against CPU baselines using simulated datasets Communicating findings and limitations to supervisors

title: DSO Internshi
text:
DSO Internshi > Technical Focus & Stack
The work was conducted in a constrained, offline Linux environment with AMD GPUs. As CUDA was not an option, GPU development was done using HIP and C++, which required adapting parallel programming concepts to a different ecosystem. Once I had the build files for the parrallelised clustering programs, I then ran benchmarking scripts written in python to to compare the output of multiple algorithms against our evaluation metrics Link to my GPU Programming notes: HIP Programming

title: DSO Internshi
text:
DSO Internshi > Approach & Execution > Algorithm Selection
After an in depth study of the context and problem, I began by surveying common density-based clustering algorithms, focusing on their computational characteristics and parallelization potential. DBSCAN, HDBSCAN, and Mean Shift were evaluated due to their relevance to the existing workflow.

title: DSO Internshi
text:
DSO Internshi > Approach & Execution > Parallelization Strategy
After preliminary experimentation, HDBSCAN was selected as the most promising candidate in terms of flitering out noise, speed and accuracy for our context. Rather than attempting to parallelise the entire algorithm end-to-end, I decomposed it into multiple logical stages and parallelised each component independently where feasible.

title: DSO Internshi
text:
DSO Internshi > Challenges & Constraints > Technical Challenges
I had no prior hands-on experience with GPU parallel programming, which required rapidly building intuition around memory models, synchronization, and performance bottlenecks. Many existing parallel implementations were written in CUDA, making them unsuitable for direct reuse in a HIP-based environment. The provided library that was meant to help convert CUDA to HIP code did not really work Attempting to adapt highly optimised libraries (e.g. optimised HDBSCAN implementation from scikit-learn) proved difficult due to tightly coupled data structures that were not designed for modular reuse.

title: DSO Internshi
text:
DSO Internshi > Challenges & Constraints > Environmental & Process Constraints
The fully offline environment significantly slowed iteration, debugging, and dependency management. Strict security processes, while necessary, introduced additional friction in development and testing workflows.

title: DSO Internshi
text:
DSO Internshi > Results & Outcomes 
The GPU-parallel implementation achieved approximately 10× speedup over CPU-based versions under default configurations, with performance gains increasing significantly as dataset size grew. Importantly, clustering quality and accuracy remained comparable to the CPU baseline, suggesting that the performance improvements did not come at the cost of correctness.

title: DSO Internshi
text:
DSO Internshi > Reflections & Key Learnings
One of the most important lessons was the importance of rigorous and representative testing. Early results appeared extremely promising, but further testing and consultation revealed that our initial evaluation did not sufficiently cover edge cases and real-world distributions. This led to significant corrections and more conservative conclusions.
